Dark Funnel Campaign - Berlin: Help Firefox understand what‚Äôs in the dark funnel, by participating in this campaign and spreading the light! We want to understand where Firefox downloads come from.

So far, we know that 30% of Firefox installs come from the official Mozilla website or from known partners. The other 70% come from mystery download sources that we call ‚Äúthe dark funnel‚Äù. Some are friendly sites, but others put users at risk of getting old editions, a bad experience or even malicious installs.

Dark Funnel Campaign - Berlin: Help Firefox understand what‚Äôs in the dark funnel, by participating in this campaign and spreading the light! We want to understand where Firefox downloads come from.

So far, we know that 30% of Firefox installs come from the official Mozilla website or from known partners. The other 70% come from mystery download sources that we call ‚Äúthe dark funnel‚Äù. Some are friendly sites, but others put users at risk of getting old editions, a bad experience or even malicious installs.

Rust / Servo Hackathon

Rust / Servo Hackathon: Learn more Rust, improve Servo or bring your own project! We are looking forward to a fun weekend.

This independent hackathon at the Coredump hackerspace (https://coredump.ch) is focussed on Servo, the next generation browser engine from Mozilla: https://servo.org/.
If you've never taken a closer look at the project, don't worry! There are a lot of beginner-friendly tickets marked as "easy" in the issue tracker.

Whether you are new to Rust or already know about it, we want you!

Introduction to WebExtensions

Introduction to WebExtensions: Firefox is drastically changing its extension system and replacing it with the Chrome-like WebExtensions. Chrome-like is an empty description for you? Perfect, Martin will explain what WebExtensions are, why you should care about them and what to do if you have an extension for Firefox that you will have to port over. For those already familiar with the Chrome extension API, the talk will point out the differences and nuances to check when porting.

IoT Hackathon Lausanne: Since February 2016 Mozilla is experimenting with IoT. There are currentl 4 different projects that are going on, but we would like to see other ideas we can all work on together. Gave a talk about Connected Devices at the techmeetups.ch in Fribourg
Finished the last organization parts for the Connected Devices hackathon in Lausanne, Switzerland

Mozilla and our experiments around Smart Home: Last december it became clear that Mozilla will shift its focus to Connected Devices. In
the first two months of 2016 it became clear as well, that Mozilla will sunset Firefox OS after the version 2.6 release in May. Even though the smartphone might still be relevant in the IoT, we will focus on how we can use the power of the Web for IoT. In this talk Michael will show a few demos (might still be alpha by then) and show you the new, exiting path for the future.

Million Mask March - Zurich: Currently there is a discussion in Swiss parliament to reform the current law regarding digital law enforcement. In privacy-concerned circles this reform is seen as a massive decrement of privacy of Swiss people. One of the means to increase the enforcement would be a trojan horse-like tool which would be installed on people's computers. Therefore there will be a demonstration in Zurich to get us heard and get as many attention to the topic as possible, so not only geeks see the problem.

Register at http://firefoxosappdaysch.eventbrite.com/ !

de:hacking meetup: This will be a meetup for German-speaking Mozilla developers (volunteers and employees). If you're not German-speaking but live in a German speaking territory (Germany, Switzerland, Austria, ...), feel free to join us as well!

The event is planed to happen at the Mozilla office in Berlin.

The event organizer is julian dot viereck at googlemail dot com.
